TY  - JOUR
T1  - Incomplete Information and the Liquidity Premium Puzzle
AU  - Chen, Yingshan
AU  - Dai, Min
AU  - Goncalves-Pinto, Luis
AU  - Xu, Jing
AU  - Yan, Cheng
Y1  - 2020/10/12
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2021/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2020.3726
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2020.3726
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 5703
EP  - 5729
VL  - 67
IS  - 9
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We examine the problem of an investor who trades in a market with unobservable regime shifts. The investor learns from past prices and is subject to transaction costs. Our model generates significantly larger liquidity premia compared with a benchmark model with observable market shifts. The larger premia are driven primarily by suboptimal risk exposure, as turnover is lower under incomplete information. In contrast, the benchmark model produces (mechanically) high turnover and heavy trading costs. We provide empirical support for the amplification effect of incomplete information on the relation between trading costs and future stock returns. We also show empirically that such amplification is not driven by turnover. Overall, our results can help explain the large disconnect between theory and evidence regarding the magnitude of liquidity premia, which has been a longstanding puzzle in the literature. This paper was accepted by Kay Giesecke, finance.
AB  - We examine the problem of an investor who trades in a market with unobservable regime shifts. The investor learns from past prices and is subject to transaction costs. Our model generates significantly larger liquidity premia compared with a benchmark model with observable market shifts. The larger premia are driven primarily by suboptimal risk exposure, as turnover is lower under incomplete information. In contrast, the benchmark model produces (mechanically) high turnover and heavy trading costs. We provide empirical support for the amplification effect of incomplete information on the relation between trading costs and future stock returns. We also show empirically that such amplification is not driven by turnover. Overall, our results can help explain the large disconnect between theory and evidence regarding the magnitude of liquidity premia, which has been a longstanding puzzle in the literature. This paper was accepted by Kay Giesecke, finance.
